The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Sunday, December 26, 2004 

 BRIEFS

 Chinsurah, Dec. 25: Chattu Das, who was sent to jail six months ago for killing his father, killed his mother at their South Gopalpur home last night.

 Chattu and his friends broke open the door of their house in Balagarh and fired at the lady, according to his stepsister, Monika Das.

 Berhampore: Police arrested three persons for the death of a housewife on Friday night, including her husband. Beli Mondal was burnt to death allegedly by her in-laws at Jola under Raghunath police station in Berhampore. The same night, another housewife, Asha Saha (27) of Ourangabad under Suti police station, committed suicide by taking poison. 

 Calcutta: The state urban development minister, Ashok Bhattacharjee, will hold a meeting with officials of the Calcutta Improvement Trust on Monday to review the work of the organisation. CIT officials said all the pending projects of the trust, including the sale of 7,000 rented flats would be discussed at the meeting.

 Calcutta: A delegation of legislators from north Bengal met governor Gopalkrishna Gandhi earlier this week at Raj Bhavan and placed their demands regarding the development of the region. The delegation, including Nirmal Das, Dasarath Tirkey, and Prasanta Narayan Majumder, also demanded that Alipurduar be declared a separate district. The MLAs also made the governor aware about the crisis in tea industry. Gandhi, it is learnt, heard the legislators for about half an hour.

 Krishnanagar: A Bangladeshi intruder was shot dead by Border Security Force personnel on Friday evening. Officials said the unidentified person was shot near Naserer Para village in Hogolberia police station area of Nadia district. The body was later handed over to Bangladesh Rifles officials , sources said.

 Krishnanagar: Three jute godowns caught fire on Friday afternoon at Bara Andulia village in Chapra police station area.Officials said jute worth Rs 25 lakh was damaged.

